# Security Fundamentals

This document covers three core information security concepts:

- 🔺 CIA Triad
- 🔑 AAA (Authentication, Authorization & Accounting)
- 💾 Three States of Data

---

# 🔺 CIA Triad

The **CIA Triad** is the foundation of information security. Every security control exists to protect one or more of these three principles.

## CIA Principles

| Principle | Definition | Goal | Real-world Example | Common Threats | Security Controls |
|-----------|------------|------|--------------------|----------------|-------------------|
| **Confidentiality** | Ensures information is accessible only to authorized users. | Prevent unauthorized disclosure. | Only HR can access employee salary records. | Data breaches, insider threats, credential theft, eavesdropping | Encryption, MFA, RBAC, VPN, Access Control Lists (ACLs) |
| **Integrity** | Ensures data remains accurate, complete, and unaltered. | Prevent unauthorized modification. | Financial records cannot be changed without authorization. | Malware, SQL Injection, file tampering, ransomware | Hashing, Digital Signatures, Checksums, Version Control, File Integrity Monitoring (FIM) |
| **Availability** | Ensures systems and data are available when needed. | Prevent service disruption. | Company website remains accessible 24/7. | DDoS attacks, hardware failure, ransomware, power outages | Backups, Redundancy, High Availability (HA), Load Balancers, Disaster Recovery |

---

## 💡 Easy Way to Remember

| Principle | Think Of |
|-----------|----------|
| **Confidentiality** | 🔒 Keep secrets secret |
| **Integrity** | ✔️ Keep data correct |
| **Availability** | 🟢 Keep systems running |

---

## Example

Imagine an **online banking application**.

- 🔒 **Confidentiality** → Only the account owner should see their account balance.
- ✔️ **Integrity** → No one should be able to modify transaction history.
- 🟢 **Availability** → Customers should be able to access the banking website whenever they need.

